Earth is 4.54 billion years old. Shrink that to one 78-year life and see where you actually fall.
{{< /lead >}}

*The planet is 4.54 billion years old. Shrink that to one median lifespan, 78 years, and watch where you actually fall.* ***Every human who ever lived fits in the final two days.***

**Anchored to today.** In this version the 78-year life ends right now, on <span class="now-date">May 30, 2026</span>. Age 0 is Earth's birth and age 78 is this exact moment, so every age, clock time, and 'life left' below is a real countdown to <span class="now-date">May 30, 2026</span>.

> *Read the whole thing top to bottom, or skim the colored timeline and open only the eons that pull at you. The detail is tucked inside the drop-downs.*

---

## The scale, in one number

Every year you live equals about **58.2 million years** of Earth history. Everything below follows from that.

| One unit of your life | equals this much Earth history |
| --- | --- |
| **1 year** | about 58.2 million years |
| **1 month** | about 4.85 million years |
| **1 week** | about 1.12 million years |
| **1 day** | about 159,000 years |
| **1 hour** | about 6,640 years |
| **1 minute** | about 111 years |
| **1 second** | about 1.84 years |

> *One second of your life is almost two full years of the planet's story. Snap your fingers and two years go by. Blink and you miss a century.*

